The good news: `exit_mmap` takes `mmap_write_lock`. That means, as long as MGLRU holds a `mmap_read_trylock`, `exit_mmap` has to wait. *But*, that means MGLRU might block the dying process. But wait. If MGLRU calls `cond_resched`, then the process can get the write lock. So that seems safe.

But then I thought about another lock: `exit_mmap` can also hold a `mmap_read_lock`. So, if `exit_mmap` *has* the read lock, MGLRU can *try* to acquire a read lock, and it can succeed. So now both MGLRU and `exit_mmap` are reading the memory map at the same time. The danger here is that `exit_mmap` is calling `unmap_vmas`, which rips up the page table entries at the same time MGLRU might be reading them. That sounds bad! However, the `unmap_single_vma` call does acquire page table locks. MGLRU has to acquire page table locks to clear access/young bits. However, the locks on page table entries should protect the contents of the page table entries! So concurrent execution seems *okay*.

